[[File:'64 Mercury Park Lane Sedan (Orange Julep '07).jpg|thumb|250px|1964 Mercury Park Lane 4-door Hardtop ("Marauder" fastback roofline)|left]]
[[File:1965 Mercury Park Lane (5125290361).jpg|left|thumb|200x200px|1965 Mercury Park Lane 2-Door Hardtop]]
[[File:1966 Mercury Park Lane 2-Door Hardtop.JPG|thumb|left|1966 Mercury Park Lane two-door hardtop]]
For the 1964 model year, the Mercury Park Lane made its return as the Mercury division expanded its model line.  Above the Monterey and newly reintroduced Montclair, the Park Lane again topped the Mercury line.  In contrast to the previous generation, the Park Lane used the same wheelbase as other Mercury lines, differing primarily in trim.

As the highest-priced, premium trim, many Park Lanes were fitted with the option of a "breezeway" reverse-slant retractable rear window (first used on the Turnpike Cruiser and the 1958-1960 Continental).  In addition, Mercury offered the Park Lane with a fastback roofline as part of Marauder option package (seen on any full-size Mercury); the fastback design proved popular on its Ford Galaxie 500 counterpart.

For 1965, the chassis of full-size Ford and Mercury cars were redesigned; the Mercury line was given a much more slab-sided appearance.  For 1967, to complement the Mercury Marquis (available only as a 2-door hardtop), the [[Mercury Brougham|Park Lane Brougham]] was introduced as a sub-model of the Park Lane.  For an option on hardtop coupe/convertible models, the Brougham introduced "yacht deck paneling" body trim (essentially the same simulated woodgrain [[DI-NOC]] used for the Colony Park); "yacht deck paneling" was a rarely ordered option.

As the division redesigned its full-size line for 1969, the Marquis was expanded to a full model range, taking over the place of the Park Lane (the Brougham would largely be replaced by the later [[Mercury Grand Marquis|Grand Marquis]]).
